 bass with [[Wynn Stewart]] at the Nashville Nevada Club in Las Vegas...Merle was another one of those rugged individualists who, like me, was trying to make sense of all the nonsense in the music business.  We became buddies for life.\u201d{{sfn|Nelson, Willie; Ritz, David|2015|p=187}}\n\nNelson, who covered [[Joni Mitchell]] and [[Fred Neil]] on his ''[[Both Sides Now]]'' album, continued to show his appreciation for the new generation of singer-songwriters of the youth culture at the time by recording [[James Taylor]]\u2019s \u201c[[Fire and Rain (song)|Fire and Rain]].\u201d Nelson had also started cutting material by more progressive country tune-smiths like [[Mickey Newbury]] and, on this album, [[Kris Kristofferson]], a \u201cbrilliant writer\u201d{{sfn|Nelson, Willie; Ritz, David|2015|p=187}} whose \u201c[[Sunday Morning Coming Down]]\u201d contained the poetic realism similar to his own lyrics.  Nelson would rerecord the song on his tribute LP ''[[Sings Kristofferson]]'' in 1979.\n\n==Reception==\n[[AllMusic]]: \u201cOver the years, Nelson has shown that he sometimes looks at relationships differently than the average songwriter (such as \u2018[[Crazy (Willie Nelson song)|Crazy]]\u2019), with a little more thought and from new perspectives. After all, not everyone's life is moon, June, and honeymoon. Two of the finest examples of the Willie way are on this album: \u2018I'm A Memory\u2019 and, especially, \u2018What Can You Do to Me Now?\u2019\n\n{{Album reviews\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|3|5}} [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r107916|pure_url=yes}} link]\n}}\n\n==Track listing==\n#\"What Can You Do to Me Now?\" - 3:27 ([[Willie Nelson]], [[Hank Cochran]])\n#\"[[Sunday Morning Coming Down]]\" - 5:48 ([[Kris Kristofferson]])\n#\"[[I'm So Lonesome I Could Cry]]\" - 2:24 ([[Hank Williams]])\n#\"[[Fire and Rain (song)|Fire and Rain]]\" - 2:57 ([[James Taylor]])\n#\"Kneel at the Feet of Jesus\" - 2:47 (Nelson)\n#\"I'm a Memory\" - 2:24 (Nelson)\n#\"Yo